    <h1>Introduction to C Programming</h1>
    <p>C programming is a powerful general-purpose programming language developed by Dennis Ritchie in 1972. It is widely used for system programming, game development, and embedded systems.</p>

    <h2>Why Learn C Programming?</h2>
    <p>C is considered the foundation of modern programming languages. Learning C helps in understanding how programming languages work at a lower level and provides better control over hardware.</p>

    <h2>Features of C</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Simple and easy to learn</li>
      <li>Fast and efficient</li>
      <li>Low-level memory manipulation</li>
      <li>Portability across platforms</li>
      <li>Rich set of built-in functions and libraries</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Applications of C</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Operating Systems</li>
      <li>Embedded Systems</li>
      <li>Game Development</li>
      <li>Database Systems</li>
      <li>Compilers and Interpreters</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Basic Structure of a C Program</h2>
    <pre>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  printf("Hello, World!\n");
  return 0;
}
    </pre>
    <p>This is a simple C program that prints "Hello, World!" to the console.</p>

    <h2>Key Components:</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><b>#include <stdio.h></b> - Includes the standard input-output library.</li>
      <li><b>main()</b> - The starting point of any C program.</li>
      <li><b>printf()</b> - A function to display output.</li>
      <li><b>return 0;</b> - Indicates successful program termination.</li>
    </ul>

